This is a college frat house party film, so in that aspect it gets one star for almost feeling like a docudrama, and the supplements are more thorough than one would ever normally see for a film this low brow - so it gets one more.

This Johnny Lechner is apparently a legend in the college community for his ability to "get high school chicks" even into his fourteenth year of going to college. The story follows two underlings as they navigate the tribulations of college partying as taught by this Lechner guy (who has apparently made it onto Letterman in the real world). I suppose if I were in college and felt that all females are there strictly for being naked, having sex, then disposing of them for more "high school chicks" - then I might dig this film. There isn't really any acting or competent camera work, this is just strictly a 24 hour frat house party caught on film.

The supplements contain 5 minutes of alternate/deleted scenes, 5 1/2 minutes of John Reisig's stand up (a couple light laughs), two different commentaries that were as enlightening as one can expect for this, and a 20 minute interview with this Fossil (Lechner) guy. Essentially he relays the importance of his lifelong pursuit of going to college, getting high school chicks and drinking.

The film is amateurish, and caters to those that feel college is nothing more than a ruse. It might appeal to those that want college to be that way or they dream about how to score all the hedonism possible while forging scholarships and using the system. I can watch a film for entertainment purposes, but it has to have some value, and there is no value here. Film stock is bad, the camera out of focus through most of the film, the sound is wretched and the cover art is ripped from Girls Gone Wild. Enjoy.
